<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite class="citation web cs1"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://relarchive.byu.edu/MPNC/descriptions/poems.html">"Abstract of <i>Poems, religious, historical, and political</i>"</a>. Harold B. Lee Library/Online Collections at BYU<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2008-06-13</span></span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Abstract+of+Poems%2C+religious%2C+historical%2C+and+political&amp;rft.pub=Harold+B.+Lee+Library%2FOnline+Collections+at+BYU&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Frelarchive.byu.edu%2FMPNC%2Fdescriptions%2Fpoems.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFAston2014" class="citation journal cs1">Aston, Warren (22 April 2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://ldsmag.com/article-1-14243/">"Remembering Mother in Heaven"</a>. <i>Meridian Magazine</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">16 September</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Meridian+Magazine&amp;rft.atitle=Remembering+Mother+in+Heaven&amp;rft.date=2014-04-22&amp;rft.aulast=Aston&amp;rft.aufirst=Warren&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fldsmag.com%2Farticle-1-14243%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFHarrison1894" class="citation journal cs1">Harrison, William Chase (15 April 1894). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/stream/juvenileinstruct298geor#page/263/mode/1up">"Our Mother in Heaven: Companion Hymn to E.R. Snow's 'Invocation'<span class="cs1-kern-right"></span>"</a>. <i>The Juvenile Instructor</i>. <b>29</b> (8): 263–264<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">16 September</span> 2017</span>. <q>Oh my Mother, thou that dwellest / In thy mansions up on high, / Oft methinks I still remember / How you bade your child goodbye; / How you clasped me to your bosom, / Bade me a true son to be / E're I left my / Father's mansion, / To dwell in mortality. / How you gave me words of counsel / To guide aright my straying feet; / How you taught by true example / All of Father's laws to keep; / While I strive in this probation, / How to learn the gospel truth, / May I merit your approval / As I did in early youth. / Tis recorded in your journal / How you stood by Father's side, / When by pow'rs that are eternal / Thou wast sealed His goddess bride. / How by love and truth and virtue, / E'en in time thou did'st become, / Through your high exalted station, / Mother of the souls of men. / When of evil I've repented, / And my work on earth is done, / Kindest Father, loving Mother, / Pray forgive your erring son. / When my pilgrimage is ended, / And the victor's wreath I've won, / Dearest Mother, to your bosom / Will you welcome home your son?</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Juvenile+Instructor&amp;rft.atitle=Our+Mother+in+Heaven%3A+Companion+Hymn+to+E.R.+Snow%27s+%27Invocation%27&amp;rft.volume=29&amp;rft.issue=8&amp;rft.pages=263-264&amp;rft.date=1894-04-15&amp;rft.aulast=Harrison&amp;rft.aufirst=William+Chase&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fstream%2Fjuvenileinstruct298geor%23page%2F263%2Fmode%2F1up&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i><a href="/wiki/Journal_of_Discourses" title="Journal of Discourses">Journal of Discourses</a></i>, vol. 9, p.&#160;286</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFRosetti2022" class="citation journal cs1">Rosetti, Cristina (2022-04-01). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.dialoguejournal.com/articles/o-my-mother-mormon-fundamentalist-mothers-in-heaven-and-womens-authority/">"<span class="cs1-kern-left"></span>'O My Mother': Mormon Fundamentalist Mothers in Heaven and Women's Authority"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Dialogue:_A_Journal_of_Mormon_Thought" title="Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought">Dialogue</a></i>. <b>55</b> (1). <a href="/wiki/University_of_Illinois_Press" title="University of Illinois Press">University of Illinois Press</a>: 133. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.5406%2F15549399.55.1.05">10.5406/15549399.55.1.05</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISSN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISSN (identifier)">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/issn/0012-2157">0012-2157</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Dialogue&amp;rft.atitle=%27O+My+Mother%27%3A+Mormon+Fundamentalist+Mothers+in+Heaven+and+Women%27s+Authority&amp;rft.volume=55&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=133&amp;rft.date=2022-04-01&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.5406%2F15549399.55.1.05&amp;rft.issn=0012-2157&amp;rft.aulast=Rosetti&amp;rft.aufirst=Cristina&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dialoguejournal.com%2Farticles%2Fo-my-mother-mormon-fundamentalist-mothers-in-heaven-and-womens-authority%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFMorrill2006" class="citation book cs1">Morrill, Susanna (2006). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=-Q0pRe-KOSYC&amp;pg=PA55"><i>White Roses on the Floor of Heaven: Mormon Women's Popular Theology, 1880-1920</i></a>. New York City: Routledge, Taylor &amp; Francis. pp.&#160;55, 108. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0415977355" title="Special:BookSources/0415977355"><bdi>0415977355</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=White+Roses+on+the+Floor+of+Heaven%3A+Mormon+Women%27s+Popular+Theology%2C+1880-1920&amp;rft.place=New+York+City&amp;rft.pages=55%2C+108&amp;rft.pub=Routledge%2C+Taylor+%26+Francis&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.isbn=0415977355&amp;rft.aulast=Morrill&amp;rft.aufirst=Susanna&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D-Q0pRe-KOSYC%26pg%3DPA55&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-20">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSmith2018" class="citation book cs1">Smith, William Victor (5 February 2018). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://deseretbook.com/p/textual-studies-of-the-doctrine-and-covenants-the-plural-marriage-revelation?variant_id=161792-paperback"><i>Textual Studies of the Doctrine and Covenants: The Plural Marriage Revelation</i></a>. Sandy, UT: Greg Kofford Books, Inc. pp.&#160;170–171. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1589586901" title="Special:BookSources/978-1589586901"><bdi>978-1589586901</bdi></a>. <q>A heaven that mirrored earthly process and form required God to have a heavenly female partner to procreate the offspring of God. But polygamy rewrote God as a polygamist, who required multiple partners (thence the meme of Mothers in Heaven) to create His human family. ... With the end of polygamy, any theology on Heavenly Mothers, never as popular as the singular Mother, largely disappeared from official discourse.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Textual+Studies+of+the+Doctrine+and+Covenants%3A+The+Plural+Marriage+Revelation&amp;rft.place=Sandy%2C+UT&amp;rft.pages=170-171&amp;rft.pub=Greg+Kofford+Books%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2018-02-05&amp;rft.isbn=978-1589586901&amp;rft.aulast=Smith&amp;rft.aufirst=William+Victor&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fdeseretbook.com%2Fp%2Ftextual-studies-of-the-doctrine-and-covenants-the-plural-marriage-revelation%3Fvariant_id%3D161792-paperback&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-21">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFMoench_Charles1988" class="citation journal cs1">Moench Charles, Melodie (Fall 1988). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/Dialogue_V21N03_75.pdf">"The Need for a New Mormon Heaven"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. <i>Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought</i>. <b>21</b> (3): 83. <q>During the era of polygamy some suggested that she is only one of many mothers in heaven. They reasoned that procreation of spirit children could be accomplished more efficiently if Heavenly Father could impregnate many heavenly mothers, just as exalted mortals' procreation of spirit children could be accomplished more efficiently if exalted mortal males could impregnate many wives.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Dialogue%3A+A+Journal+of+Mormon+Thought&amp;rft.atitle=The+Need+for+a+New+Mormon+Heaven&amp;rft.ssn=fall&amp;rft.volume=21&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=83&amp;rft.date=1988&amp;rft.aulast=Moench+Charles&amp;rft.aufirst=Melodie&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dialoguejournal.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2Fsbi%2Farticles%2FDialogue_V21N03_75.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFEmbry1994" class="citation web cs1">Embry, Jessie L. (1994). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20181107044102/https://heritage.utah.gov/history/uhg-history-polygamy-2">"The History of Polygamy"</a>. <i>heritage.utah.gov</i>. Utah State Historical Society. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://heritage.utah.gov/history/uhg-history-polygamy-2">the original</a> on 2018-11-07<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2018-12-31</span></span>. <q>Those involved in plural marriages after 1904 were excommunicated; and those married between 1890 and 1904 were not to have church callings where other members would have to sustain them. Although the Mormon church officially prohibited new plural marriages after 1904, many plural husbands and wives continued to cohabit until their deaths in the 1940s and 1950s.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=heritage.utah.gov&amp;rft.atitle=The+History+of+Polygamy&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.aulast=Embry&amp;rft.aufirst=Jessie+L.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fheritage.utah.gov%2Fhistory%2Fuhg-history-polygamy-2&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-23">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFSwanson2013" class="citation book cs1">Swanson, Vern G. (2013). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Rss1CgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PT251">"Christ and Polygamy"</a>. <i>Dynasty of the Holy Grail: Mormonism's Holy Bloodline</i>. Springville, UT: Cedar Fort, Inc. pp.&#160;247–259. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781462104048" title="Special:BookSources/9781462104048"><bdi>9781462104048</bdi></a>. <q>Dr. William E. Phipps noted that the belief that 'Jesus married, and married often!' was used to encourage and promote the doctrine of polygamy amongst timid Latter-Day Saints ... By the late-1850s the idea that more than one woman was married to Jesus was widely accepted among Mormon circles. ... As if the concept of Christ's polygamy was not unsettling enough, Mormonism even taught in the nineteenth century that God the Father had a plurality of wives as well.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Christ+and+Polygamy&amp;rft.btitle=Dynasty+of+the+Holy+Grail%3A+Mormonism%27s+Holy+Bloodline&amp;rft.place=Springville%2C+UT&amp;rft.pages=247-259&amp;rft.pub=Cedar+Fort%2C+Inc.&amp;rft.date=2013&amp;rft.isbn=9781462104048&amp;rft.aulast=Swanson&amp;rft.aufirst=Vern+G.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DRss1CgAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPT251&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFPratt1853" class="citation journal cs1">Pratt, Orson (October 1853). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/stream/seereditedbyorso01unse#page/158/mode/1up">"The Seer"</a>. <i>The Seer</i>. <b>1</b> (10): 158,172<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">9 October</span> 2017</span>. <q>Inasmuch as God was the first husband to her, it may be that He only gave her to be the wife of Joseph while in this mortal state, and that He intended after the resurrection to again take her as one of his wives to raise up immortal spirits in eternity. ... We have now clearly shown that God the Father had a plurality of wives, one or more being in eternity by whom He begat our spirits as well as the spirit of Jesus His First Born, and another being upon the earth by whom He begat the tabernacle of Jesus.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Seer&amp;rft.atitle=The+Seer&amp;rft.volume=1&amp;rft.issue=10&amp;rft.pages=158%2C172&amp;rft.date=1853-10&amp;rft.aulast=Pratt&amp;rft.aufirst=Orson&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fstream%2Fseereditedbyorso01unse%23page%2F158%2Fmode%2F1up&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-25">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFWilcox1992" class="citation book cs1">Wilcox, Linda (30 June 1992). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=T6bHN1Ka12cC&amp;pg=PA72">"The Mormon Concept of a Mother in Heaven"</a>. <i>Sisters in Spirit: Mormon Women in Historical and Cultural Perspective</i>. Champaign, IL: University of Illinois Press. p.&#160;72. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0252062965" title="Special:BookSources/0252062965"><bdi>0252062965</bdi></a>. <q>An LDS Seminaries and Institutes student manual also hints at the possibility of multiple heavenly mothers. In a diagram entitled 'Becoming a Spirit Child of Heavenly Parents,' an individual (male) [12] is depicted with upward lines to his heavenly parents, the one parent labeled 'Heavenly Father' (caps), the other labeled 'a heavenly mother' (lower case). Book of Mormon Student Manual, 2 vols. (Salt Lake City: Church Educational System, 1976), 1:218</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=The+Mormon+Concept+of+a+Mother+in+Heaven&amp;rft.btitle=Sisters+in+Spirit%3A+Mormon+Women+in+Historical+and+Cultural+Perspective&amp;rft.place=Champaign%2C+IL&amp;rft.pages=72&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Illinois+Press&amp;rft.date=1992-06-30&amp;rft.isbn=0252062965&amp;rft.aulast=Wilcox&amp;rft.aufirst=Linda&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DT6bHN1Ka12cC%26pg%3DPA72&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1215172403"><cite id="CITEREFKramer2014" class="citation thesis cs1">Kramer, Bradley H. (2014). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/handle/2027.42/107060/bhkramer_1.pdf?sequence=1">"Chapter 5. Heavenly Mothers"</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span>. <i>Keeping the Sacred: Structured Silence in the Enactment of Priesthood Authority, Gendered Worship, and Sacramental Kinship in Mormonism</i> (Doctorate of Philosophy). University of Michigan. p.&#160;115<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">26 Nov</span> 2019</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Adissertation&amp;rft.title=Keeping+the+Sacred%3A+Structured+Silence+in+the+Enactment+of+Priesthood+Authority%2C+Gendered+Worship%2C+and+Sacramental+Kinship+in+Mormonism&amp;rft.inst=University+of+Michigan&amp;rft.date=2014&amp;rft.aulast=Kramer&amp;rft.aufirst=Bradley+H.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fdeepblue.lib.umich.edu%2Fbitstream%2Fhandle%2F2027.42%2F107060%2Fbhkramer_1.pdf%3Fsequence%3D1&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHeavenly+Mother+%28Mormonism%29" class="Z3988"></span></span>
